'''''100,000 Cobbers''''' is a 1942 dramatised documentary made by director [[Ken G. Hall]] for the Australian Department of Information during [[World War II]] to boost recruitment into the armed forces. [[Grant Taylor (actor)|Grant Taylor]], [[Joe Valli]] and [[Shirley Ann Richards]] play fictitious characters.

==Plot==
Four young Australian men and an ex-[[World War I]] veteran who takes ten years off his age ([[Joe Valli]]) volunteer to fight in the Australian army and train over six months to become soldiers. They attend a cabaret then depart to go overseas.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article54894412 |title=Men of Services In New Film. |newspaper=[[Sunday_Mail_(Adelaide)|The Mail (Adelaide, SA : 1912 - 1954)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=11 October 1941 |accessdate=12 February 2012 |page=6 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

==Production==
Filming began on 15 September 1941 and took 14 days.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article27945947 |title=FILM OF ARMY LIFE. |newspaper=[[Sydney_morning_herald|The Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)]] |location=NSW |date=13 September 1941 |accessdate=12 February 2012 |page=12 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> It was filmed at Liverpool Military camp using national servicemen and a number of actors who were given leave to make the movie.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article17767008 |title=Women's News<U+2014> AT STUDIO ARMY LEAVE FOR FILM PLAYERS. |newspaper=[[Sydney_morning_herald|The Sydney Morning Herald (NSW : 1842 - 1954)]] |location=NSW |date=3 October 1941 |accessdate=12 February 2012 |page=3 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>[[Shirley Ann Richards]] plays a chiropractor.

